**************************************************************************
                         WEAPON AND ARMOUR CODING GUIDELINES
**************************************************************************
Note:   A wizard is allowed to have only 1 unique item per 100 rooms, and
        the number of exceptional items allowed is also restricted.  See
        'wizhelp 4.14 (uniques)' for details.


***************************************************************************
                         ARMOUR CODING
***************************************************************************

Note:   For armor coding, there are rules and there are guidelines. You
        can look at the rules as being related to balance issues and not
        negotiable. This is because players always gravitate towards the
        best things. Anything that is overpowered will tend to disrupt
        overall balance to a disproportionately large extent. Guidelines
        are more thematic elements that you should try to follow for
        consistency, but may be violated for other thematic reasons.

        Don't get carried away making all your items really good since
        too many good items will make the game too easy for players.

***************************************************************************
                         ARMOUR TYPES/SETTINGS
***************************************************************************
When creating your armour, you must make sure you specify its
COVERAGE TYPE, COMPOSITION, MATERIAL, QUALITY and SIZE. This is done
by using set_new_type(), set_material(), and set_quality().

-----------------------------Coverage Types------------------------------
Valid basic coverage types:
TORSO, LEGS, BOOTS, HELMET, AMULET, SHIELD, RING, CLOAK, GLOVES,
SHOULDERS, AURA.

RING and AMULET each allow two worn items. Ordinary ring and amulet
objects will use the first available matching slot. The other basic
coverage types normally allow one worn item.

Valid composite coverage types:
ARMOUR, ARMOR - same as TORSO|LEGS
FULL_SUIT - same as TORSO|LEGS|HELMET|GLOVES|BOOTS

These are the ONLY allowed armour types.  If you set it to something
else, the game will reset it to ARMOUR. However, you may OR the
types together to create armors with unique coverage.

-----------------------------Size----------------------------------------
Size should be specified for all new and recoded armors.  However, only
SHIELD types are currently affected by size.

Valid sizes: SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE, HUGE
NOTE: Shield size is *very* important for guild restrictions.

------------------------------Composition--------------------------------
Valid compositions:
CLOTHES, PADDED, HIDE, STUDDED, CHAIN, BANDED, SCALE, PLATE.

Common armour identities are defined in <basic_armour.h>. New armour should
use set_armour_template() when a stock form fits, or use the closest semantic
ARMOUR_* identity instead of assembling size, composition, and coverage bits
by hand:

        set_armour_template("breastplate");

or:

        set_new_type(ARMOUR_BREASTPLATE);

Templates provide default material, aliases, weight, value, and generated
material/quality prose. Builders may override those defaults after selecting
the template. Clonable stock forms live in
/objects/standard_equipment/armour/. If a recurring armour form has no
suitable identity, extend <basic_armour.h> rather than copying a new bit
combination into area code. MAGICAL may be added deliberately to an identity;
it is not an armour composition.

If the composition you want is NOT in this list, talk to an IMP+ about
what category to put it in to.

-------------------------------Material----------------------------------
Valid materials are described in 'wizhelp 4.16 (materials)'.

Example: set_material(MAT_STEEL);

Materials can be mixed. MAT_NATURAL means woven of grass, etc. If you
want any materials added to this list, tell us now, as it necessitates
rebooting the mud to add new ones.

-------------------------------Quality-----------------------------------
Quality is a percentage range INCREASE of the armor's quality over the
average armor of the appropriate composition. Use a negative value to
make armors that are worse than average. Wearing an armor with quality
under -100 will result in an overall penalty to the player over not
wearing anything at all.

Quality can be set using set_quality();

-------------------------------Examples----------------------------------
All of these but size can be mixed. Here are some examples:

leather jerkin      : set_new_type(ARMOUR_LEATHER_JERKIN);
                      set_material(MAT_LEATHER);
                      set_quality(0);
ogre's robe         : set_new_type(ARMOUR_SIZED(ARMOUR_ROBE, LARGE));
                      set_material(MAT_CLOTH);
                      set_quality(-30);
leather leggings    : set_new_type(ARMOUR_LEATHER_LEGGINGS);
                      set_material(MAT_LEATHER);
                      set_quality(0);
small shield        : set_new_type(ARMOUR_BUCKLER);
                      set_material(MAT_WOOD|MAT_STEEL);
                      set_quality(-20);
plate               : set_new_type(ARMOUR_PLATEMAIL);
                      set_material(MAT_STEEL);
                      set_quality(0);
full plate          : set_new_type(ARMOUR_FULL_PLATE);
                      set_material(MAT_STEEL);
                      set_quality(0);
adamantite full     : set_new_type(ARMOUR_SIZED(ARMOUR_FULL_PLATE, SMALL));
   battle armour      set_material(MAT_ADAMANTITE);
   (dwarf sized)      set_quality(30);

*************************************************************************
                         ARMOUR RULES
*************************************************************************

Quality ranges normally fall between -100 (for armor that is useless
because it's falling apart, to +40 for normal armors of the highest
quality workmanship. The quality must roughly reflect the long/short
descs of the item.

Any armor with a quality above 40 is considered exceptional, and any
armor with a quality above 60 must be unique. Under no circumstances
should quality be above 100.

*************************************************************************
                         ARMOUR GUIDELINES
*************************************************************************
Note:   These values are guidelines only, for thematic purposes.

