---------------------------------------------------------

***************************************************************************
**                             *IMPORTANT*                               **
**  You can only have 1 powerful (unique) item per 100 rooms coded!!!!!  **
**                                                                       **
***************************************************************************

The weights are a general guideline.  If you think something is heavy,
make it heavy!  Remember that weight here also represents bulk, so a
cloak that is light but awkward could still have a high weight.

The actual usefulness of a piece of armour is determined internally based
on the coverage, composition and quality of the armour, modified by the
armour specialization setting of a player. Thus the "armour class" of
a particular piece of armor is only so useful in determining how good a
piece of armour is. All things being equal, the quality of the armour
is a linear modifier over the default (quality 0). Thus an armour with
a quality of 50 is 50% better than an armour of quality 0.


===========================================================================
**************************************************************************
                         WEAPON CODING GUIDELINES
**************************************************************************

Note:   For weapon coding, there are rules and there are guidelines. You
        can look at the rules as being related to balance issues and not
        negotiable. This is because players always gravitate towards the
        best things. Anything that is overpowered will tend to disrupt
        overall balance to a disproportionately large extent. Guidelines
        are more thematic elements that you should try to follow for
        consistency, but may be violated for other thematic reasons.

***************************************************************************
                         WEAPON TYPES/SETTINGS
***************************************************************************
 
Weapon identities are defined in <basic_weap.h>. New weapons should include
that header and use the closest semantic WEAPON_* identity instead of
assembling size and damage bits by hand:

        set_new_type(WEAPON_DAGGER);

The identity supplies the standard size, damage types, and FINESSE, MARTIAL,
FOCUS, POLE, or MISSILE role where appropriate. MAGICAL and a deliberately
exceptional TWO_HANDED flag may be added to the identity. If a recurring
weapon form has no suitable identity, extend <basic_weap.h> rather than
copying a new bit combination into area code.

Clonable stock weapons live in /objects/weapons/. They provide sensible
material, quality, weight, value, and description defaults. Area weapons with
custom behavior should continue to inherit WEAPON and use a WEAPON_* identity.

Valid sizes       : SMALL, MEDIUM, LARGE, HUGE
NOTE:   Size is *very* important for guild restrictions.  The size of
        the weapon relative to the wielder affects wieldability as well.
        A weapon that is relatively HUGE compared to a wielder will
        automatically be used two-handedly.

NOTE:   A SMALL weapon is something that is about 1.5 feet or so long, and
        smaller. A MEDIUM weapon falls in the 1.5 to 3 feet or so. LARGE
        weapons range from about 3 to 5 feet long, and anything bigger is
        HUGE. This is a rough guideline for most melee weapons (swords,
        axes, maces etc) and some types of weapons are generally longer
        for their categories (e.g. bows and polearms).

Valid damage types: BLUNT, SLASH, CLEAVE, PIERCE

Valid weapon types: POLE, MISSILE, MAGICAL, TWO-HANDED
NOTE:   You don't have to use a weapon type if it doesn't fit one of the three
        categories.  A weapon which uses the POLE type is automatically
        considered TWO-HANDED, as is a MEDIUM or larger MISSILE.
 
Use one identity and add only deliberate exceptional flags. Examples:
dagger           : set_new_type(WEAPON_DAGGER);
rapier           : set_new_type(WEAPON_RAPIER);
short sword      : set_new_type(WEAPON_SHORTSWORD);
saber            : set_new_type(WEAPON_SABER);
long sword       : set_new_type(WEAPON_LONGSWORD);
greatsword       : set_new_type(WEAPON_GREATSWORD|TWO_HANDED);
sap              : set_new_type(WEAPON_SAP);
sling            : set_new_type(WEAPON_SLING);
mace             : set_new_type(WEAPON_MACE);
short bow        : set_new_type(WEAPON_SHORTBOW);
war hammer       : set_new_type(WEAPON_WARHAMMER);
battleaxe        : set_new_type(WEAPON_BATTLEAXE);
staff            : set_new_type(WEAPON_STAFF);
halberd          : set_new_type(WEAPON_HALBERD);

The difference between SLASH and CLEAVE is in the manner of damage; CLEAVE
puts a lot of force behind the blow for sheer power in a small hit area,
while SLASH tends to be a raking attack, cutting sidewise into the target.
Axes, cleavers, halberds, and the like are CLEAVE, while swords, daggers,
and claws are SLASH.

Weights are set using:

        set_weight(int iWeight);

The usefulness of a weapon is set using:

        set_quality(int iQuality);

Similar to armor settings, set_quality ranges from -100 for a totally
worthless weapon to 100 for the maximum allowed class for a high end
unique. Any quality setting above 40 is considered exceptional, and any
over 60 is unique.

***************************************************************************
                         WEAPON RULES
***************************************************************************

The damage type and size of a weapon are limited only to be consistent
with the thematic qualities of the weapon. For example, you can't make
a normal longsword and call it a CLEAVE|BLUNT. You can make a 'fairy-
sized longsword' and make it SMALL though.

Weight should be consistent with thematic qualities. When setting weapon
weights, try to start with a similar size/type guideline weapon, and
adjust it to fit the particular circumstances.


*********************************************************************
                         WEAPON GUIDELINES
*********************************************************************
Note:   These values are guidelines only, for thematic purposes.

TYPE                 SIZE      DAM TYPE       WEIGHT
------------------------------------------------------------------
AXE
  hatchet            SMALL     CLEAVE           2
  battleaxe          MEDIUM    CLEAVE           3
  great axe          LARGE     CLEAVE           5
------------------------------------------------------------------
BOW
  short bow          MEDIUM    PIERCE           2
  long bow           LARGE     PIERCE           2
  crossbow           MEDIUM    PIERCE           3
  great bow          HUGE      PIERCE           3
------------------------------------------------------------------
DAGGER
  butter knife       SMALL     PIERCE           1
  curved dagger      SMALL     PIERCE/SLASH     1
  dirk               SMALL     PIERCE/SLASH     1
  heavy kris         SMALL     PIERCE           2
------------------------------------------------------------------
HAMMERS/MACES
  carpenter's hammer SMALL     BLUNT            1
  smithing hammer    MEDIUM    BLUNT            3
  warhammer          MEDIUM    BLUNT            3
  mace               MEDIUM    BLUNT            3
  heavy mace         LARGE     BLUNT            4
  maul               HUGE      BLUNT            6
------------------------------------------------------------------
POLEARMS
  spear              LARGE     PIERCE(POLE)     3
  bardiche           HUGE      CLEAVE(POLE)     7
  halberd            HUGE      CLEAVE(POLE)     6
  lance              HUGE      PIERCE(POLE)     4
  naginata           HUGE      SLASH(POLE)      5
  pike               HUGE      PIERCE(POLE)     4
------------------------------------------------------------------
STAVES
  stick              SMALL     BLUNT            1
  cane               MEDIUM    BLUNT            2
  quarterstaff       LARGE     BLUNT(POLE)      3
------------------------------------------------------------------
SWORDS
  shortsword         MEDIUM    SLASH/PIERCE     2
  rapier             MEDIUM    PIERCE           2
  broadsword         MEDIUM    SLASH            3
  scimitar           MEDIUM    SLASH            3
  longsword          LARGE     SLASH/PIERCE     4
  bastard sword      LARGE     SLASH            5
  greatsword         HUGE      SLASH            6
-----------------------------------------------------------------

"Weapon class" is no longer set explicitly by builders on weapons,
except in extremely unusual situations (consult an IMP+ in that case).
Instead use set_quality() to set the overall power of the weapon. The
quality is a linear modifier over the default usefulness of a weapon.

The actual usefulness of a weapon is determined internally based on
the material_composition of a weapon, aspects of it's type and quality.


